{
  "doc_id": "34286",
  "text": "Our data raise questions about the pathophysiology of de novo IBD after intestinal transplantation, which has been shown to occur at a rate up to 10-fold higher than in the general population. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] 26 Recent evidence has shown that inflammatory disease in the gut is largely mediated by ILCs, particularly ILC3s. 19 Specifically, the dysregulation of Th17 cytokines, which are expressed by ILC3s, is thought to contribute to the development of IBD and other inflammatory and autoimmune conditions. 27 Similarly, dysregulation of the Th1 response, driven by the transcription factor T-bet and characterized by IFN-γ secretion, has been associated with rejection after ITx. [CITATION_3] 28 More detailed analyses in additional patients might reveal associations between these phenomena and the turnover and function of various ILC populations.",
